Peel and grate the @garlic{3%cloves}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one). Finely chop the @black olives{60%g}(finely chopped). Pick the leaves from the @rosemary{1%sprig}(leaves picked and finely chopped). Grate the @parmesan cheese{40%g}(grated).

> Fennel adds a sweet liquorice flavour that fuses beautifully with lamb and olives.

Pick the delicate leaves (technically they're called fronds!) from the @fennel{2}(fronds removed and discarded). Chop the root from the base and discard. Very, very thinly slice your fennel widthways. Tip: Ideally use a #vegetable peeler{} if you have one as you want it to be almost translucently thin.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{splash} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add your garlic and rosemary. Cook until your garlic just starts to change colour then add your fennel with a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Cook for around ~{6%minutes} until your fennel is soft.

Tip: Don't brown the fennel – turn down the heat and add a splash of water if it's too hot.

Add the @lamb mince{500%g} and break it up using a #wooden spoon{}. Season with another pinch of @salt{pinch} and a few good grinds of @black pepper{few grinds}. Add your olives. Boil a #pot{} of water with pinch of salt for the pasta.

Once your lamb has browned add the @chopped tomatoes{2%400g cans}. Fill the tin(s) a quarter with water, swill it around and add to your sauce.

Tip: You can add @?sugar{pinch} at this point to lift the flavour even more.

Turn the heat to low and simmer gently for as long as your hunger allows, preferably at least ~{10%minutes}. This is your ragu!

When your ragu is 6 mins from ready add the @wheat spaghetti{400%g} to the pot of boiling water. Cook for ~{9%minutes} or until 'al dente'.

Tip: 'Al dente' simply means it's cooked but still has a bit of firmness in the middle.

Once your pasta is cooked, drain it and add to your fennel and lamb ragu. Toss everything together with your parmesan and you're done!